Fixes #14: GetCookies fails to deserialize expiry when using chromedriver

Chrome appears to store cookies with an expiry time that can include milliseconds. When using the
chromedriver, this internal representation is returned (ie. Expiry: 1475462515.303742) which causes
the Go json parser to fail. This fixes the issue by avoiding deserializing the Expiry field upfront,
and handling it separately.

Comment out support for msedgedriver on Linux until it's out of preview.

The linux driver version is in preview and not in sync with other operating systems. This means that the LATEST_RELEASE_ file is not usable for it. It has a separate _LINUX file AND the download file lives in a deferent location than the current `base_url`. This combination of differences makes it difficult to support Linux builds within the current implementation. I was able to make it sort of work, but the implementation was messy and seemed hack-ish. I think the best thing to do is to hold off on supporting Linux builds until the general release is available. It's currently in a preview release (insider) only.

test names in test descriptions and during filtering.

Previously, browser-specific test names (e.g. testABC@Chrome) were
reported as failing, but when Surefire tried to rerun them, #filter()
failed to find matching tests. Now rerunFailingTestsCount parameter
works correctly.
Also, previously e.g. in IntelliJ Idea on running testABC with e.g.
@Chrome and @Firefox annotations, three tests were shown in the
test run tab: testABC, testABC@Chrome, testABC@Firefox, with testABC
being completely useless. Now this is fixed and only testABC@Chrome and
testABC@Firefox would be shown.
Also, more precise test filtering is supported in -Dtest parameter.
Before, it enabled/disabled tests for all the browsers, now it is
possible to use e.g. -Dtest=testABC@Chrome, which would only run
test for Chrome. -Dtest=testABC does not work anymore, but this is
easy to work around by using -Dtest=testABC@* which would run testABC
for all the configured browsers.

This reverts commit f52ad8b2b0553cac1cb3d397ae4a3d61e357e0eb.

* Update test suite to detect when Chrome didn't load

The commit with a problem caused no drivers to load but the tests
did not detect this as they were looking to see what args were
specified not what was the result of those args with regard to what
drivers loaded.

This commit updates the test suite to better detect the problem. It
captures the stdout and checks it for Chrome instead of just checking
the args.

With this in place I now have a failing test with my problematic code
from before.

* Make selenium use only the drivers specified

This removes the previous attempt to do this, `--detect-drivers`. That
option would be better named as "--load-drivers" as it won't load any
drivers regardless if specified the path via the CLI.

According to this discussion:

https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/issues/8928

The `-I` driver is what is needed to specify what drivers should be
loaded. Therefore for each driver we are providing an explicit path we
are also indicating that driver should be loaded. Any without a -I
will not get loaded.

I updated the failing test so it does explicitly load the firefox driver
(to avoid the jar throwing an error about no drivers being loaded) and
then have the test verify that Chrome is not in the output indicating
that other drivers such as Chrome did not load.

The possible values for `-I` doesn't seem well documented (that I could
find). The code seems to compare the CLI value to the "display name"
for each driver info class:

https://github.com/SeleniumHQ/selenium/blob/9546dba7a5aefe45ff8fe2bbc1039819dde10672/java/src/org/openqa/selenium/grid/node/config/NodeOptions.java#L460

Therefore to get a complete list of the right values I just looked at
all the implementations of the "getDisplayName" method.

I have personally manually tested chrome, firefox and chromium edge.
I don't have a win32 system to test IE and the legacy version of
Edge but based on the display name it *should* work just fine.

Fix Conditional HTTP Requests (#667)

* Partially revert 2da8f60 (checking only top-level folder)

When a file within a folder is updated the folder does not change it's
timestamp. Only if a new file/folder is added/removed will the
timestamp change.

The commit message on 2da8f60 doesn't make clear if the developer
thought the top-level folder would update the timestamp but that is
my assumption. It's also not clear what failure was happening with the
test but my assumption is what it was the etag issue I'm work to
correct.

This commit updates the test so it does the folder walk it was doing
previously and verifies that ALL files have the same timestamp. Since
the previous code to walk the tree was made a while back I did make
some style changes to match with current project conventions.

* Refactor writing of downloaded files

The primary goal is to have a single function that handles the writing
so we have a single place where we can save the etag from the HTTP
response.

This also DRYs up some existing code including fixing a small issue
with `installSingleFile`. The other `install` functions all correctly
install the `error` event handler on the writableStream. The
`installSingleFile` installs it on the download stream (which already
has one) and leaves the writableStream without

* Record etag when saving downloaded stream

This will allow for a conditional HTTP request later.

Using the FS promise API is simpler than the callback API so I used that
for writeFile but to avoid `fs` confusion just extracted the relevant
methods from each module.

* Use etag for conditional HTTP request

The previous commit updated the system so the etag is saved next to
the file downloaded. This actually uses that info to make a proper
conditional HTTP request.

With this in place we can actually remove the special exception for
Edge as well. It wasn't that conditional HTTP requests were not
working but just that the MD5 hash was not the right tag to send for
that server.

* Last minute change made lint complain. Fix

* Make compat with v12 of NodeJS

In NodeJS v12 it is:

  require('fs').promises

instead of

Adjustments to `start` Options (#660)

* Adjustments to start options

Could not get the test suite to pass. Ran into two issues due to
options (or lack of options) being passed to the `start` function.
Rather than adjust the test suite to pass the necessary option I thought
it would be better to adjust the API to have defaults so the options are
not necessary.

Spawn Options Stdio
===================

This defaults to `pipe`. With this default the behavior I was getting
is that the `checkStarted` was always failing. This was obviously not
an issue at some point. I am guessing that the selenium jar file changed
it's behavior so that it didn't fully boot up until some stdio activity
occurred and since this library is not interacting with that pipe
it remained not booted.

I noticed the `bin/selenium-standalone` script did not have a problem
booting the server. After a bit of debugging determined it is because
it sets the spawnOptions.stdio to `inherit`. This allows that
sub-process to not be blocked by stdio.

I considered also defaulting spawnOptions.stdio to 'inhert' with the
API but I'm not sure writing on top of the parent's STDIO is the
right default behavior. It would seem being quite and squashing
stdio (sending to /dev/null) is a better default so I set it to
`ignore`. Obviously if this is not the right behavior for a specific
application they can always override.

===================================

Merge pull request #5 from tazjin/feat/arbitrary-capabilities

Add argument for adding arbitrary capabilities to make-session

Add argument for adding arbitrary capabilities to make-session

This change lets make-session accept an optional
'additional-capabilities' key argument, the content of which is
spliced into the plist used to generate the capabilities sent to
Selenium.

This can be used to make, for example, headless Chrome sessions for
use in CI systems:

```lisp
(with-session
     ;; Configure headless Chrome instance:
    (:additional-capabilities
     '((:chrome-options . ((:args . #("--headless"))))))

  (some-stuff))
```

(Note: The indentation change is the recommend indentation in Emacs'
lisp-mode)

Refactor module interface and up our demo game

Given that the Selenium WebDriver uses promises, it doesn't make sense for the
module to provide a callback interface.

While we're at it, refactor the exported interface to be a function that takes a
config object and returns a Q promise. That promise is resolved when the
targeted WebDriver server comes up and is rejected after a configurable number
of retries (5 by default).

The resolved value is a `WebDriver` instance. It provides a reference to
`lib/node/webdriver` via its `webdriver` property.

Finally, update the demo to print the results of the search instead of the
document title.

find and find1

* Implemented the simpler API for finding (as noted in the original PR)
* Added variants for finding children of previously found elements

* Updated the WebElement to store an Id (if the attribute exists), and an ElementId (the unique UUID given to elements by the webDriver).

When an element is being used as the basis for a sub-query, it will now try:

   find1(Id) - if an 'id' attribute exists.  If that fails...
   find1(elementId) - with the current web-drvier.  If that fails...
   find1(query, index) - using the original query and index.

It's a little leaky, but will work in the vast majority of cases.  We should discuss whether the edge cases are problematic.

* Updated the unit test that points to the meddbase jobs page.  The live url had changed

* Updated the console test-app to make it obvious if it worked or not.

Flipped the condition on waitUntil

* It previously would wait for false.  But it should 'wait until condition is true'
* The dual of that is `doWhile`, which is: 'do while condition is true'.

This will break anything that uses waitUntil, but this is such a big deal that it needs to be done, IMHO.

Also updated the documentation to reflect that, as it was totes unclear.

fix(xbox): Fix several reliability issues (#47)

This fixes several issues with reliability, especially when running
tests in a loop back-to-back without a delay between.  In those cases,
the Xbox One would frequently fail to launch or to uninstall the app.

Specific changes:

 - Await session closure on shutdown (fixed in base package v1.1.4)
 - Log but swallow app uninstall errors (don't report to the client)
 - Retry when app launch fails (after a delay to let Xbox recover)

ci: Add monorepo release workflow (#41)

All packages will be released by one workflow.

To make this work right, the base package had to be moved to a folder
(base/).  Otherwise, release-please would have released updates to
that package if any files were changed in any other package.

This also simplifies the way the backends reference the base package,
using the "workspaces" feature, introduced in NPM v7.

Finally, this reformats the changelogs for future automated updates by
release-please.

on new PRs.  When we add tests later, the workflow will activate them
through npm test.

ci: Expand PR title validation triggers (#30)

Force-pushes from automated PRs (like release-please) do not seem to
trigger any of the normal PR triggers (opened, edited, synchronize).
In fact, even an exhaustive list of types will not work.  So here we
add triggers for reviews, so that the validation will run after
someone approves such a PR.  This is critical since this is a required
status check in most of our repos.  If the workflow doesn't run, the
release PR can't be merged.

ci: Require PRs in conventional commits syntax (#28)

This will allow automated generation of changelogs and releases based
on PR titles.

docs: Fix reference to non-existent package

There is no NPM package for the "fake" backend.  There would be no
point in publishing it.  But the docs were following the same
structure as every other backend, and gave instructions for
installation from NPM.  This could lead to an attack in which someone
registers the package name and is tricked by our docs into installing
something malicious.

This updates the docs for the "fake" backend to remove any reference
to a package name or installation via NPM.

Mouse over to element only when clicking with mouse

Previously `click`ing would first mouse over to element. This has
been removed and now we hover the mouse on the element only when
left clicking with mouse.

This solves and issues when using remote web driver with gecko, which
currently does not support mouse movement correctly. It also makes
senses to move the mouse only if clicking with the mouse.

See #16
Add v0.3.1 release notes to changelog

Introduce a common interface for locating web elements

Previously, when looking for a nested element, client code had to
start from the `BrowserDriver` and then iterate a tree of
`WebElementDriver`s.

This change makes it easier to navigate a tree of elements by
introducing a common `WebElementLocator` interface shared by both
the `BrowserDriver` and the `WebElementDriver`. Selecting a nested
element can now be done with a simple for loop.

Note that `ElementLocator` has been renamed to `ElementFinder` to
avoid confusion with the new `WebElementLocator` interface.

А именно, выделите вспомогательные классы для работы с главной страницей (откуда выбирается товар), для работы со страницей товара (откуда происходит добавление товара в корзину), со страницей корзины (откуда происходит удаление), и реализуйте сценарий, который не напрямую обращается к операциям Selenium, а оперирует вышеперечисленными объектами-страницами.

зайти в админку

If the first `rm -rf` attempt fails to delete everything, make
a second attempt before reporting an error to the caller.

Sometimes we fail to delete all of the contents of Firefox’s temporary profile on quit. I think this is caused by a race: we attempt the `rm -rf` before Firefox has fully shutdown, and files get rewritten after we delete them.

The FirefoxDriver will flag its presence by setting
window.navigator.webdriver === true on every page.

For now, the original fingerprinting method (setting an attribute on
documentElement) remains.

Roll back addition of @license tag to all JS files.

This bloats the atoms considerably with no benefit.

NO-OP: Wrap existing license headers, unchanged, in @license JsDoc block.
Closure compiler keeps such blocks unchanged, with line ends preserved, in the output.
That makes it harder for the users to violate the license by not including the notice
with build artifacts.

I am also going to add Software Freedom Conservancy+Apache2 headers like these
to all JS files that do not have *any* license header (which is actually useful,
unlike this). I am not going to *change* any license notices, obviously.

arguments or return values.

This is used for types that cannot be synchronously converted to their

toJSON() function)

When we call toJSON() on an object to convert it to it's wire format, we
must recurse on the returned object to make sure all properties are
properly converted.

for chaining), but before this commit was instead returning
the string passed to it.
